Lab Steps

1. Create a Management Group

A new Azure Management Group was created to logically organize subscriptions and apply governance controls at scale.

Purpose
Centralized governance
Subscription organization
RBAC inheritance
Policy management
2. Assign RBAC to a Group

Instead of assigning permissions directly to users, a group named HelpDesk was used.

Why Groups?
Easier administration
Better security management
Reduced permission sprawl
Simplified onboarding/offboarding
3. Assign Built-in Role

The following built-in role was assigned:

Virtual Machine Contributor
Permissions Included
Start/Stop VMs
Restart VMs
Manage VM settings
Permissions Excluded
No access to RBAC changes
No access to subscription ownership
4. Create a Custom Role

A custom RBAC role was created using a JSON definition.

Objective

Customize permissions beyond built-in Azure roles.

Modification Performed
Removed Microsoft Support-related actions/permissions
Key Learning

Azure custom roles are defined using JSON templates.

Example structure:

{
  "Name": "Custom VM Operator",
  "IsCustom": true,
  "Actions": [],
  "NotActions": [],
  "AssignableScopes": []
}
RBAC Inheritance Concept

Azure RBAC follows hierarchical inheritance.

Permissions assigned at higher scopes automatically flow downward.

Hierarchy Example
Management Group
    ↓
Subscription
    ↓
Resource Group
    ↓
Resources

This reduces repetitive role assignments and simplifies governance.

